It's good but not worth the hassle of crowd , wait time , parking in sf , etc. you can find comparable southern food in the Bay Area with less crowds

Decent prices for really good! I tend to find myself disappointed at southern style restaurants that aren't actually in the south-- but not here! Start with some crawfish beignets for sure.

This place is fantastic. Their food is like a party in my mouth. Came here with a party of three on a Thursday afternoon at 11:30 or so. We wrote our name down on the chalkboard and waited about 20 minutes until we were seated. Not really complaining; for the high volume of people coming in and out, it was pretty speedy. Plus, it gave us time to look at the extensive menu. Through the power of yelp, we decided to get the lobster beignets. I ordered pork belly grits -- purely because I have never had grits before -- while my friends ordered an oyster omelette and a regular spinach and goat cheese omelette. The beignets were so good. Melt in your mouth good. The crunchy layer outside kept the inside nice and warm. The filling was chopped lobster and had a creamy, salty sauce. The red powder (paprika?) atop the beignet kept falling everywhere but I didn't even care. And that's saying something, because I'm a neat freak when I eat. My grits and pork belly with a poached egg was fantastic. Covered with a generous layer of cheese, the grits were just what I imagined them to taste like. Slightly grainy but still flavorful. The pork belly was soft and tender. The poached egg was literally perfect. I cut it open and it was soft and runny. I tried my friend's oyster omelette and it was beautiful. The omelette was nicely cooked, with no runny insides. It wasn't overly dry but the texture was fluffy and smooth. The oysters weren't overly cooked and super chewy, which tends to happen with some places. After the beignet and half of my grits, I was full. The waiter was attentive and refilled our water. When we asked for more utensils he gave them to us. He also helped us split the check when we asked. My only complaint was that our table was slightly too small for the three of us but that's not really something they can fix. I love this place. I will definitely be back here for brunch, most likely on a weekday.

I've had this place bookmarked for a while and I'm so glad I was finally able to check it out this past trip to the city. We arrived about 40 minutes before closing and only waited about 15 minutes to get a table for 4 on a Sunday night. The place was packed and a live band was playing. The waiting area is small and there are signs to make sure you don't block the entrance. It wasn't too bad trying to squeeze in. A busy restaurant is worth waiting for. What a great atmosphere! I ordered the gumbo with a side of biscuits. I also ordered the crawfish beignet appetizer. I think the gumbo and biscuits were by far my favorite. I would definitely come back just for the gumbo. I'm not a big seafood eater, so the chunks of chicken, andouille sausage, and okra were perfecttt!!! Seasoned wonderfully with just the right amount of rice, it was a perfect way to warm up after a cold day of shopping. The biscuits were buttery and gigantic! I don't think I would order the crawfish beignets again. They were a novelty to me and I just wasn't a big fan. They're interesting and should be tried, but I wouldn't come here for them. My sister and her bf had the fried chicken and thought it was delicious. My friends had the fried chicken eggs benedict and really liked her food. Overall, I think we were all very happy with our food selection and would love to come back the next time we're in the city!

I always believed that the best crawfish was eaten in someone's backyard on a Sunday surrounded by friends and family, seeing who could eat the most the fastest. I now know it's the crawfish beignets from Brenda's, eaten with maybe a friend but better alone so you don't have to share. Gentlemen, leave your belts at home & ladies, wear your eating dress.

One of the best places for Southern food in the city, 4,000+ Yelp reviews don't lie. It's fairly inexpensive for brunch and one meal will leave you feeling full for 6-8 hours, and there's not a ton of places where you can get this type of food. If you go on a weekend, be prepared to wait (in a not-so-great neighborhood) for about 2 hours. I've gone twice on a weekday around 1 pm - 2:30 pm and not had to wait at all. Once you come, make sure to get the beignets - they are one of the best in the city. If you're here with 2 or more people, get the beignet flight - for $9.50, you'll get to try the plain, chocolate (filled with melted Ghirardelli chocolate), granny smith apple, and the crawfish. My favorites were the chocolate and granny smith apple. I like crawfish, but the cayenne pepper and all the spices were a bit too intense for me. I was afraid to breathe in cayenne pepper from the top of the beignet as I was eating. I loved the variety of flavors in the beignet sampler and the dough was fluffy, warm, and not overly sweet. Would come here and just eat beignets, but eventually I would never fit through the door. Other than that, here are the other dishes I've tried: Shrimp and Grits ($12) - Sauteed shrimp with cheddar grits and tomato-bacon gravy. This had a ton of flavor, and was almost overpowered by bacon. It also seemed like I was eating cheese with a little bit of grits, rather than the other way around. It was good in small bites, so if you're craving shrimp and grits, share this with someone else otherwise it will be too much of a good thing. For myself, I'd probably pass on getting this again. Creole Veggie Omelette ($9.50) - Loved that I could get grits (no cheese), a fluffy, buttery, fresh biscuit to accompany the omelette, all for under $10. It had a good amount of veggies inside: tomato, bell pepper, onion, corn, spinach and cheese. Cornmeal-fried Catfish Po'Boy ($9.75) - Good sandwich, but it's not like I can't find a fried fish sandwich at other places. It was a bit heavy on the remoulade sauce for my liking. Definitely a gem of a place for brunch with reasonable prices, large portions, and dishes you won't readily find elsewhere. They have good Bloody Mary's too! Don't leave without getting the beignets!

Food is literally worth the wait. Brought me back to my time in Paris. Amazing Food!! Had the Butter Pecan French Toast, Eggs Benedict Florentine, Chocolate, Apple and Regular Beignet trio.

The grits are amazing, never liked grits before this! Ask for cheese on top. The house-made cinnamon peach jam is worth eating without the cream biscuits.

Great place to eat generous and tasty Soul Food: fried chicken, okra etc. I recommend taking one large combo for two and try some appetizers. Some dishes have a little French twist, very likely inspired by the place co-owner Andre, a nice and authentic Frenchman. The atmosphere is relax there, especially at the counter. It is more trendy than what used to be the Blue Jay Cafe (predecessor at the same location), but definitely nothing over the top. The place is not too big, you can generally see the cooks in the kitchen: it is a 'human' size and not too noisy. You may want to know that it is always full. Consequently, be prepared to come early and put your name on the list.

    One of the best places for Southern food in the city, 4,000+ Yelp reviews don't lie. It's fairly inexpensive for brunch and one meal will leave you feeling full for 6-8 hours, and there's not a ton of places where you can get this type of food. If you go on a weekend, be prepared to wait (in a not-so-great neighborhood) for about 2 hours. I've gone twice on a weekday around 1 pm - 2:30 pm and not had to wait at all.

    Once you come, make sure to get the beignets - they are one of the best in the city. If you're here with 2 or more people, get the beignet flight - for $9.50, you'll get to try the plain, chocolate (filled with melted Ghirardelli chocolate), granny smith apple, and the crawfish. I was afraid to breathe in cayenne pepper from the top of the beignet as I was eating. I loved the variety of flavors in the beignet sampler and the dough was fluffy, warm, and not overly sweet. Would come here and just eat beignets, but eventually I would never fit through the door.

    Other than that, here are the other dishes I've tried:

    Shrimp and Grits ($12) - Sauteed shrimp with cheddar grits and tomato-bacon gravy. This had a ton of flavor, and was almost overpowered by bacon. It also seemed like I was eating cheese with a little bit of grits, rather than the other way around.     Cornmeal-fried Catfish Po'Boy ($9.75) - Good sandwich, but it's not like I can't find a fried fish sandwich at other places. It was a bit heavy on the remoulade sauce for my liking.

    Definitely a gem of a place for brunch with reasonable prices, large portions, and dishes you won't readily find elsewhere. They have good Bloody Mary's too! Don't leave without getting the beignets!

    4/17/2009Previous review

    SOUL FOOD TO DIE FOR, GO TO HEAVEN, AND THEN COME BACK TO EARTH!!!!

    A treasure in the tenderloin neighborhood. a dime in the dozen. and a dimond in the rough. This place has become my happy sensation when i think of the food i've experienced. I came here for the first time last week on Easter Sunday and found me a great spot to eat. We read the reviews before coming here of recommendations of what to order, the wait but the worth of it. what really got my support was the chef/owner is PINAY who is down for the french soul food cooking (absolutely loving it!) we rushed ourselves here only to find about fifteen people waiting infront of us (outside) and a list (where we were at the very bottom). i didn't mind the wait, the only thing that bothered me was starring at everyone inside eating. if your wondering about the price, super affordable with the portions you get and the taste to go along with it.

    First thoughts - those people inside need to hurry up and get out so i can get in. every person walking out has left overs!

    We waited about 40 minutes. walked in, since we were outside starring at the menu and specials, we knew right away what to order... helps keep the people shuffling in and out of this place. we ordered alot of food because we wanted to try everything. We knew first off we were going to get some Gumbo. It's funny, my mom has made gumbo before but she's from the Philippines so I always call it "filipino gumbo" and never really thought anyone else would make gumba. but at Brenda's, their Chicken Sausage Gumbo was so delicious. see our order below:

    1. Watermelon Ice Tea (so good)
    2. Bowl of Chicken Sausage and Okra Gumbo (yum to the tenth power)
    3. Crawfish with cayenne scallions and cheddar beignets
    4. side order of a pancake (huge)
    5. Grillades and Grits (with 2 eggs and a biscuit (very hearty and tasty)
    6. Cornbeef Hash with 2 eggs and a biscuit (yummy, has a pinch of spiciness)

    second thoughts - have i died and gone to heaven? why did i order this... i should have ordered much more because i want to try everything. i wish they told me the dishes can be spicy... duh... it is soul food, there should be spice.

    ALL TOO GOOD. i can go on and on forever about the watermelon icetea, bumbo, and biscuits. i plan to dip in weekly during the weekdays to get me some good breakfast and i think my order will be the watermelon icetea, gumbo, and a biscuit. oh the biscuits, are you kidding me... it's that good!

    First timers, quit being lazy, get yourself up and head over here. Yes, wait in line but the better... the more your hungry, the more you can eat. enjoy because you definately will be leaving SOULFUL from this joint.

    third thoughts - full. why are all our leftovers look like we just walked out of a grocerry store because we have bags full of leftovers.

    Until the next review...

    I've been here twice. Both times were great experiences.
    Food: I've tried the shrimp and grits, crawfish beignets, and pork belly. The grits are very flavorful and a creamy texture. The crawfish beignets had quite a kick and were unique, definitely worth a try. The pork belly came over cheddar grits and a perfectly poached egg. The pork belly was slightly crispy and worked well with the egg and salsa.
    Location: It's a small venue so the wait can be pretty long. The decor is rich to match the food and the place is always bustling.
    Service: The host was very friendly and checked in on us a few times as we waited for our table. The waiter was attentive.
    This place has some great food and is definitely worth checking out. Be ready for a wait though.

    Great place to eat generous and tasty Soul Food: fried chicken, okra etc. I recommend taking one large combo for two and try some appetizers.

    Some dishes have a little French twist, very likely inspired by the place co-owner Andre, a nice and authentic Frenchman.

    The atmosphere is relax there, especially at the counter. It is more trendy than what used to be the Blue Jay Cafe (predecessor at the same location), but definitely nothing over the top. The place is not too big, you can generally see the cooks in the kitchen: it is a 'human' size and not too noisy.  

    You may want to know that it is always full. Consequently, be prepared to come early and put your name on the list.

    We got the flight of beignets and the shrimp and grits. We almost choose another item but luckily we didn't it was a lot of food. Not a fan of the chicory coffee a little too rooty for me.

    As for the flight of beignets loved the chocolate one! the plain was good throw some jam on it if you want to add some more flavor. The savory one was not bad and the apple eh... didn't care for it at all.

    The shrimp and grits was AMAZING! I loved the tomatoes in it and the flavor was just in your face deliciousness with each bite. It looks like a heart attack with extra cheese but the cheese was not too over powering and luckily didn't give me any issues (lactose intolerant).  I will definitely come back to try other items.

    I didn't intend to come to this place but the Red Door Cafe was turning away patrons at 11am. So this was another recommendation from a friend and boy was I glad we came here. I am truly a fan!
